- Line 1: `// \` (C++ comments line 1 and continues to line 2; Rust comments only line 1)
- Line 2: `const _X: &str = r#"` (Rust opens raw string; C++ has this commented out)
- Inside raw string put `#if 0` then close `"#;` — but the close must be skipped by C++. 

Let me use the cleaner version: put C++ code first inside `#if 1`, and Rust code inside raw strings. End the file carefully so no bare `#endif` exists for Rust. I'll wrap the final `#endif` with `//` so Rust sees a comment but the backslash continues it for... no.

Simplest fix to the previous working-ish version: change last 3 lines from `#if 0` / `"#;` / `#endif` to just `"#;` preceded by something. Put `#endif` inside the raw string (before `"#;`), and make the final `"#;` line be skipped by C++ using `#if 0` ... but then unterminated #if in C++. 

Resolution: For C++, after the real main, add `#if 0` then `"#;` then `#endif`. For Rust, the raw string `_Y` opened at `const _Y: &str = r#"` swallows everything (#endif, C++ code, #if 0) up to `"#;`. Then after `"#;` Rust sees `#endif` = error. So I must ensure the final `#endif` is ALSO inside a Rust comment. Add a `//` before it won't help since it's its own line. Use: after `"#;` put nothing for Rust. So the C++ `#endif` must come BEFORE `"#;`. But then C++ `#if 0` ... `#endif` ... `"#;` — the `"#;` is now outside the #if/#endif and C++ sees `"#;` as code = error.

Solution: make `"#;` a C++ comment line: `"#; //` won't help, `"` starts a string in C++. Hmm. Put `"#;` such that C++ skips it: end C++ file with a block comment `/*` that swallows `"#;` and EOF. C++ allows comment to EOF? No, unterminated comment is error. 

Let me just test the exact fix: move #endif before "#; and make "#; invisible to C++ via being inside a C++ block comment started right after C++ main.",
